article.headline: Utah 60, Wyoming 49
article.story: SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- It wasn't just another road loss for Wyoming. Despite dropping to 0-5 away from Laramie, the Cowboys were within one point of Utah with under five minutes to play before the Utes pulled away for a 60-49 win Saturday. Andrew Bogut scored a season-high 20 points and grabbed 16 rebounds for the Utes, who won their eighth straight. "When you're on the road, you try to give yourself a chance to win, and we gave ourself a chance to win, and kept fighting back hard," Wyoming coach Steve McClain said. The difference was Utah hit key shots while the Cowboys went 1-of-6 from the field and 1-of-4 from the free-throw line down the stretch. "We get the game down to one, and we've got a stop," McClain said. "We've guarded, the shot clock's going to go out, and one, (Richard) Chaney steps up and hits a 3, and two, (Justin) Hawkins, who probably got his first 3 of the year (actually his third), he buries one. "One of them 3's doesn't go in when we guard them for 35 seconds and we might have had a chance to win the game, but it didn't work our way." "You have to step up and make shots when the game's on the line and that's something the Utah kids did," McClain said. "I liked our effort. We just didn't get enough out of people." Bogut blocked five shots and hit 8-of-13 from the floor but converted just 4 of 12 free throws and didn't score in the last 14:50. As the Cowboy defense began focusing on Bogut, Nick Jacobson found his range. Jacobson scored 13 of his 17 points in the final 13:16, including four free throws in the final minute, to keep Utah (14-3, 2-0 Mountain West) unbeaten at home this season. Mory Correa scored 14 points and Jay Straight added 11 for the Cowboys (8-7, 1-1 MWC), who scored just three points after cutting Utah's lead to 47-46 with 4:47 to play. "Of all the losses on the road, I can take more positives out of this game than I can any of them," McClain said. "I thought we had the right attitude. We were throwing the ball inside. We were running our stuff, getting wide-open looks, and we hold them to 36 percent in the first half." "I see a lot of things we can do differently when they come to our place," he said. The Utes didn't lead until the second half, but then a pair 3-pointers by Jacobson -- including a four-point play where he was fouled on the shot -- gave Utah a 46-35 advantage with 10:52 to play. The Cowboys started going inside to Correa, who scored seven points in an 11-1 run and forced Utah starting center Tim Frost to foul out. Correa scored and drew Frost's fifth foul on a runner in the lane with 4:47 remaining to close the gap to 47-46. Correa missed the free throw and then missed the front end of a one-and-one on the next possession. Jacobson and Justin Hawkins hit jumpers down the stretch and the Utes made their final eight free throws. The Utes, who rank second in the country in scoring defense, held the Cowboys to a season-low in points. Utah also outrebounded Wyoming 39-28, and kept the Cowboys without a single fast-break point. Joe Reis, who had started 46 consecutive games, did not start for Wyoming because of an injury and didn't score in seven minutes of play. Wyoming visits BYU Monday at 8:30 p.m. Utah hosts Colorado State in the Big Monday game at 10 p.m. on ESPN.
